Author: Cuvier, 1827
Critical Notes: species complex; Chaetopterus does occur in the region but which species has not yet been documented.

Author: Grube, 1863
Critical Notes: "Considering" ... "the presence of multiple species of Phyllochaetopterus in the NEP, some of which are undescribed, I would use Phyllochaetopterus sp. in your list" - Leslie Harris

Author: Moore, 1905
Critical Notes: collector name missing in metadata. Described from Japan, may not be in the NEP. Originally recorded as "Aphrodite negligens"

Author: Linnaeus, 1758
Critical Notes: Nereis procera cannot be identified without dissection. Unless it was collected & given to a taxonomist any dive observation will most likely be wrong

Author: Malmgren, 1867
Critical Notes: NEP specimens are likely to be mis-identified as the name is a holdover from when European literature dominated polychaete systematics. It was described from the Arctic & is a European species. Northern European specimens have a distinct color pattern similar to our Cheilonereis cyclurus that is very different from NEP worms id'ed as N. zonata. I would change the Galiano record to Nereis cf. zonata

Author: (Malmgren, 1867)
Critical Notes: Valid species but again an older European name that is most probably not here. What is here is Epigamia magna (Berkeley 1923)

Author: Harris (provisional species name)
Critical Notes: "Myxicola aesthetica" Leslie Harris, polychaete expert, remarks: "different NEP websites & publications report this soft-sediment worm as both M. infundibulum & M. aesthetica, which is the first part of the confusion. In Europe M. infundibulum is found in soft-sediments & M. aesthetica is the one hanging from docks & hard-surfaces so if our NEP specimens are really the same as a European species they would be M. infundibulum. However, our NEP specimens are distinctly different both morphologically & genetically from infundibulum. The second part of the confusion is what to call them. In the past several NEP species of Myxicola were described from California, Puget Sound, & Alaska. All of the original specimens need to be re-examined so we can decide what name (or names) to use in the NEP."

Author: Claus & Grobben, 1905
Critical Notes: PMLS records of Parasagitta elegans cannot be confirmed; Eukrohnia hamata Mijbius (1875), has been documented within the Salish Sea, where it occurs infrequently, being an oceanic species occasionally borne in by the intrusion of offshore waters (Lea 1955, Gardner 2013).
